Task 1: Identify and Document Pipeline Components
Step 1: Create Component Documentation File
Create a file to document each pipeline component:

nano pipeline_components.txt
Step 2: Document the Data Source
Add the following information about your data source:

=== ETL PIPELINE COMPONENTS ===

1. DATA SOURCE (EXTRACT)
   - Type: CSV File
   - Name: daily_orders.csv
   - Location: /data/incoming/
   - Format: Comma-separated values
   - Columns: order_id, customer_id, product_id, quantity, price, order_date
   - Update Frequency: Daily at 2:00 AM
   - File Size: ~50MB per file
   
   Sample Data Structure:
   order_id,customer_id,product_id,quantity,price,order_date
   1001,C001,P501,2,29.99,2024-01-15
   1002,C002,P502,1,49.99,2024-01-15
Step 3: Define Transformation Requirements
Add transformation details to the same file:

2. TRANSFORMATION LAYER (TRANSFORM)
   - Data Cleaning:
     * Remove duplicate order_id entries
     * Handle missing values in customer_id
     * Validate price > 0
     * Validate quantity > 0
   
   - Data Enrichment:
     * Calculate total_amount = quantity * price
     * Convert order_date to standard format (YYYY-MM-DD)
     * Add processing_timestamp
   
   - Data Validation:
     * Check order_id is unique
     * Verify customer_id format (C + 3 digits)
     * Verify product_id format (P + 3 digits)
   
   - Business Rules:
     * Flag orders with total_amount > $1000 as "high_value"
     * Reject orders with invalid dates
Step 4: Define Target Database
Add target database specifications:

3. TARGET DATABASE (LOAD)
   - Database Type: PostgreSQL
   - Database Name: ecommerce_db
   - Schema: orders
   - Table Name: processed_orders
   
   Table Structure:
   - order_id (INTEGER, PRIMARY KEY)
   - customer_id (VARCHAR(10))
   - product_id (VARCHAR(10))
   - quantity (INTEGER)
   - price (DECIMAL(10,2))
   - total_amount (DECIMAL(10,2))
   - order_date (DATE)
   - processing_timestamp (TIMESTAMP)
   - high_value_flag (BOOLEAN)
   
   - Load Strategy: Append new records daily
   - Error Handling: Log failed records to error table
Save and close the file (Ctrl+X, then Y, then Enter).

Task 2: Create Architecture Diagram
Step 1: Create Diagram Definition File
Use Graphviz DOT language to define your pipeline diagram:

nano etl_pipeline.dot
Step 2: Define the Pipeline Architecture
Add the following diagram code:

digraph ETL_Pipeline {
    // Graph settings
    rankdir=LR;
    node [shape=box, style=filled, fontname="Arial"];
    
    // Data Source
    source [label="DATA SOURCE\n\nCSV File\ndaily_orders.csv\n\nLocation:\n/data/incoming/", 
            fillcolor="#E8F4F8", color="#2E86AB"];
    
    // Extract Process
    extract [label="EXTRACT\n\nRead CSV File\nValidate Format\nLoad to Memory", 
             fillcolor="#FFF3B0", color="#F4A261"];
    
    // Transform Process
    transform [label="TRANSFORM\n\nClean Data\nValidate Rules\nEnrich Fields\nCalculate Totals", 
               fillcolor="#FFE5B4", color="#E76F51"];
    
    // Load Process
    load [label="LOAD\n\nConnect to DB\nInsert Records\nCommit Transaction", 
          fillcolor="#D4F1DD", color="#2A9D8F"];
    
    // Target Database
    target [label="TARGET\n\nPostgreSQL\necommerce_db\nprocessed_orders", 
            fillcolor="#C8E6C9", color="#264653"];
    
    // Error Handling
    error [label="ERROR LOG\n\nFailed Records\nValidation Errors", 
           fillcolor="#FFCDD2", color="#C62828", shape=folder];
    
    // Data Flow
    source -> extract [label="Daily\n2:00 AM"];
    extract -> transform [label="Raw Data"];
    transform -> load [label="Clean Data"];
    load -> target [label="Insert"];
    transform -> error [label="Invalid\nRecords", style=dashed];
    load -> error [label="Load\nFailures", style=dashed];
}
Save and close the file.

