Conclusion
You have successfully designed a complete ETL pipeline without writing any code. You've learned to:

Identify components: Documented source, transformation, and target layers
Design architecture: Created visual diagrams showing data flow
Define transformations: Specified cleaning, validation, and enrichment rules
Plan error handling: Designed failure paths and logging strategies
Why This Matters: Before building any data pipeline, proper design prevents costly mistakes. Your diagram serves as a blueprint for implementation and helps communicate requirements to stakeholders. This design-first approach is standard practice in data engineering.

Next Steps: In future labs, you'll implement this pipeline using Python and Apache Airflow, transforming your design into working code.

Key Takeaway: Good pipeline design considers not just the happy path, but also error handling, data quality, and operational monitoring from the start.
